{
  "The smallest living structural level of the body is the:": "",
  "Organ": "",
  "Tissue": "",
  "Molecule": "",
  "Cell": "",
  "Cells are the smallest living structural and functional units of the body, whereas molecules are chemical structures that are not independently alive.": "",
  "How many major tissue types are recognized in the human body?": "",
  "6": "",
  "4": "",
  "2": "",
  "3": "",
  "The four primary tissue types are epithelial, connective, muscle, and nervous tissue, each with distinct structures and functions.": "",
  "An organ consists of:": "",
  "Only cells and no tissues": "",
  "One tissue type only": "",
  "Only molecules and atoms": "",
  "Two or more tissue types working together": "",
  "By definition, an organ is a structure composed of at least two different tissue types that cooperate to perform a specific function.": "",
  "Which sequence is correct from simplest to most complex?": "",
  "Atom â†’ Organ â†’ Cell â†’ Tissue": "",
  "Tissue â†’ Cell â†’ Organ â†’ System": "",
  "Cell â†’ Tissue â†’ Organ â†’ Organ System â†’ Organism": "",
  "Organ â†’ Tissue â†’ Cell â†’ System": "",
  "The standard hierarchy of structural organization proceeds from atoms and molecules through cells, tissues, organs, organ systems, and finally the complete organism.": "",
  "The cardiovascular system includes the heart and:": "",
  "Blood vessels and blood": "",
  "Bronchial tubes and alveoli": "",
  "Nephrons and renal tubules": "",
  "Tendons and ligaments": "",
  "The cardiovascular system is composed of the heart, blood vessels (arteries, veins, capillaries), and blood, all working together to transport nutrients and oxygen throughout the body.": "",
  "A water molecule (Hâ‚‚O) exists at which level of organization?": "",
  "Chemical level": "",
  "Tissue level": "",
  "Cellular level": "",
  "Organ level": "",
  "Molecules such as water, proteins, and DNA are at the chemical level of organization, which is the simplest level involving atoms and molecules.": "",
  "How many major organ systems are typically recognized in the human body?": "",
  "15": "",
  "8": "",
  "5": "",
  "11": "",
  "There are 11 major organ systems in the human body, including the integumentary, skeletal, muscular, nervous, endocrine, cardiovascular, lymphatic, respiratory, digestive, urinary, and reproductive systems.": "",
  "The stomach is an example of which level of organization?": "",
  "A cell": "",
  "A tissue": "",
  "An organ system": "",
  "An organ": "",
  "The stomach is an organ because it is composed of multiple tissue types (epithelial, muscle, connective, and nervous) that work together to perform the function of digestion.": "",
  "Which tissue type transmits electrical signals throughout the body?": "",
  "Epithelial": "",
  "Nervous": "",
  "Connective": "",
  "Muscle": "",
  "Nervous tissue is specialized for generating and conducting electrical impulses (action potentials), allowing rapid communication between different parts of the body.": "",
  "All organ systems work together to maintain:": "",
  "Homeostasis and life": "",
  "Only digestion": "",
  "Only movement": "",
  "Only circulation": "",
  "The 11 organ systems cooperate to maintain homeostasis, which is the stable internal environment necessary for survival and proper body function.": "",
  "What is the chemical level of organization?": "",
  "The simplest level, involving atoms and molecules such as proteins and DNA": "",
  "The level at which the entire organism functions": "",
  "The level at which organs form systems": "",
  "The level at which cells group together to form tissues": "",
  "The chemical level is the most fundamental level of structural organization, encompassing atoms (carbon, hydrogen, oxygen) and molecules (water, glucose, DNA) that form the building blocks of all living structures.": "",
  "What is a tissue in anatomical terms?": "",
  "A single cell performing a specific function": "",
  "A group of similar cells working together to perform a common function": "",
  "Another name for an organ system": "",
  "A structure made of multiple organs": "",
  "A tissue is defined as a group of structurally similar cells, along with their extracellular matrix, that work together to carry out a specific function such as protection, support, or contraction.": "",
  "What does the term 'organ system' mean?": "",
  "A group of organs that cooperate to accomplish a common purpose": "",
  "A type of tissue found in the brain": "",
  "The chemical bonds between molecules": "",
  "A single organ working independently": "",
  "An organ system is a group of organs that work together to perform a broad function, such as the digestive system (mouth, esophagus, stomach, intestines, liver, pancreas) breaking down and absorbing food.": "",
  "What is the organismal level of organization?": "",
  "The level of a single tissue type": "",
  "The level of atoms combining into molecules": "",
  "The highest level, representing the entire living human being as all systems function together": "",
  "The level of individual cells": "",
  "The organismal level is the highest level of structural organization, representing the complete living human in which all organ systems function interdependently to sustain life.": "",
  "What is connective tissue?": "",
  "Tissue that only transmits nerve impulses": "",
  "Tissue that only covers body surfaces": "",
  "Tissue found only in the heart": "",
  "The most abundant and diverse tissue type that supports, connects, and protects body structures": "",
  "Connective tissue is the most widespread and varied tissue type in the body, including bone, blood, cartilage, and adipose (fat), all characterized by cells scattered within an extracellular matrix.": "",
  "What does 'cellular level' mean in the hierarchy of organization?": "",
  "The level at which atoms combine to form molecules": "",
  "The level describing the whole organism": "",
  "The level at which molecules assemble into the smallest living units of the body": "",
  "The cellular level is where molecules combine to form cells, which are the smallest independently living units capable of carrying out life processes such as metabolism, growth, and reproduction.": "",
  "What is epithelial tissue?": "",
  "Tissue that contracts to produce movement": "",
  "Tissue that covers body surfaces, lines cavities, and forms glands": "",
  "Tissue that transmits electrical signals": "",
  "Tissue that provides structural support through a hard matrix": "",
  "Epithelial tissue forms the coverings and linings of body surfaces and cavities (such as the skin and the lining of the digestive tract) and also forms glands that secrete substances like hormones and enzymes.": "",
  "What does 'muscle tissue' mean?": "",
  "Tissue that produces blood cells": "",
  "Tissue that stores minerals": "",
  "Tissue specialized for covering body surfaces": "",
  "Tissue specialized for contraction and movement": "",
  "Muscle tissue is specialized for contraction, enabling movement of the body (skeletal muscle), pumping of blood (cardiac muscle), and movement of substances through hollow organs (smooth muscle).": "",
  "What is the organ level of organization?": "",
  "The level at which all systems work together": "",
  "The level of atoms and molecules": "",
  "A group of similar cells performing one function": "",
  "The level at which two or more tissue types combine to form a discrete structure with a specific function": "",
  "The organ level is where two or more different tissue types unite to form a recognizable structure, such as the heart or liver, that performs one or more specific functions.": "",
  "What does 'homeostasis' mean in the context of organ systems?": "",
  "The breakdown of food into nutrients": "",
  "The tendency of the body to grow larger over time": "",
  "The process by which cells divide": "",
  "The maintenance of a relatively stable internal environment despite external changes": "",
  "Homeostasis refers to the body's ability to maintain a stable internal environment (such as temperature, pH, and blood glucose levels), and it relies on the coordinated efforts of all 11 organ systems.": "",
  "A medical student is examining a tissue sample under a microscope and sees flat cells lining a blood vessel. She notes that this represents which level of organization?": "",
  "Organ system level": "",
  "A group of similar cells (such as the flat endothelial cells lining a blood vessel) working together represents the tissue level of organization, which is one step above the cellular level.": "",
  "During a lab dissection, a student cuts open the stomach and observes muscle layers, a mucous lining, connective tissue, and nerve fibers. This observation best illustrates which concept?": "",
  "That the stomach is an organ system": "",
  "That the stomach is an organ composed of multiple tissue types": "",
  "The chemical level of organization": "",
  "That the stomach is a tissue": "",
  "The presence of multiple tissue types (epithelial lining, muscle layers, connective tissue, and nervous tissue) within a single structure confirms that the stomach is an organ, which by definition contains at least two different tissue types.": "",
  "A patient presents with kidney failure, and the doctor explains that the kidneys, ureters, bladder, and urethra all work together. This group of organs functioning together represents which level of organization?": "",
  "The organ level": "",
  "The tissue level": "",
  "The cellular level": "",
  "The organ system level": "",
  "Multiple organs (kidneys, ureters, bladder, urethra) cooperating to perform the function of urine formation and excretion represents the organ system level, specifically the urinary system.": "",
  "A nurse observes that a patient's blood test reveals abnormal hemoglobin molecules. This problem originates at which level of organization?": "",
  "Chemical (molecular) level": "",
  "Hemoglobin is a protein molecule, so an abnormality in its structure represents a problem at the chemical (molecular) level, which can then cascade upward to affect cells, tissues, and organs.": "",
  "A physical therapist is treating a patient whose skeletal muscles have atrophied from disuse. The therapist explains that muscles, bones, and joints must all function together for movement. This interdependence best illustrates which principle?": "",
  "That tissues are the highest level of organization": "",
  "That a single organ can function independently of all others": "",
  "That the chemical level controls all body functions": "",
  "That organ systems work interdependently to achieve body functions": "",
  "The muscular and skeletal systems must work together for movement, demonstrating that organ systems are interdependent rather than isolated, which is a fundamental principle of the levels of organization.": "",
  "A pathologist examining a biopsy sample identifies a group of similar cells embedded in a hard, mineralized matrix. Based on the levels of organization, this sample most likely represents:": "",
  "Smooth muscle tissue": "",
  "Bone (osseous) tissue, a type of connective tissue": "",
  "Epithelial tissue": "",
  "Nervous tissue": "",
  "Cells embedded in a hard, mineralized extracellular matrix is characteristic of bone (osseous) tissue, which is classified as connective tissue at the tissue level of organization.": "",
  "A biology student is asked to classify DNA within the levels of structural organization. She correctly places it at which level?": "",
  "DNA is a large molecule (macromolecule) composed of nucleotide subunits, placing it at the chemical level of organization, even though it is found inside cells.": "",
  "A patient is diagnosed with liver cirrhosis, which damages all tissue types within the liver. A medical student realizes this demonstrates that the liver is classified as an organ because:": "",
  "It contains multiple tissue types including epithelial, connective, muscle, and nervous tissue": "",
  "It contains only one cell type": "",
  "It is made of a single tissue type": "",
  "It functions as an entire organ system by itself": "",
  "The liver qualifies as an organ because it contains epithelial tissue (hepatocytes and bile ducts), connective tissue (blood vessels and stroma), smooth muscle, and nerve fibers, all working together to carry out metabolic functions.": "",
  "During a clinical rotation, a nursing student learns that a patient's red blood cell count is dangerously low. The student correctly identifies that individual red blood cells represent which level of organization?": "",
  "Individual red blood cells are at the cellular level of organization, as each is a single cell specialized for oxygen transport, even though collectively they contribute to blood tissue.": "",
  "A trauma surgeon explains to her team that when a patient suffers severe injuries, every organ system can be affected because all levels of organization are interconnected. Which statement best supports this explanation?": "",
  "Only the organ level is important in trauma care": "",
  "Organ systems function independently and are not affected by damage to other systems": "",
  "Damage at any level of organization can cascade to affect higher levels, ultimately threatening the organism": "",
  "The chemical level has no relevance to clinical medicine": "",
  "The levels of organization are hierarchically interconnected, so damage at any level (chemical, cellular, tissue, organ, or system) can cascade upward and affect the entire organism, which is why trauma care addresses all levels simultaneously.": ""
